        "discriminators": [
          "Same bubble physics as WATER-BUBBLES, but VISCOUS. A thick liquid supports larger, slower bubbles: by Minnaert's relation a bigger cavity resonates LOWER, so pitch_hz sits around 200 Hz against water's ~900 Hz, the centroid drops by an octave and a half, and low_band_energy dominates.",
          "The rising chirp survives but is slower and more damped: pitch_slope_semitones_per_second is still positive (~+20 st/s) but roughly half water's, and viscosity blunts the transient (softer envelope, longer decay).",
          "Slower too: onset_rate_per_second ~3/s of fat gloops versus water's ~8/s.",
          "Against WATER-FIZZ: the opposite extreme of the same axis — fizz is thousands of tiny high-frequency bubbles, this is a few large low-frequency ones.",
          "Against LIQUID & MUD-MOVEMENT: BUBBLES has resolvable pitched pops; MOVEMENT is a continuous gloopy bed."
        ],
        "confusable_with": [
          "WATRBubl",
          "LIQMvmt",
          "LIQSuct",
          "WATRDran",
          "GEOMudpot"
        ]
      }
